now. So to resolve that, we can use the stage function, again, this is a ggplot stage function,

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:41.959
to map Y at the start to satisfy the stat, and then remap to Y in the after stat to satisfy

00:17:41.959 --> 00:17:47.119
the geom. And then that gets us the layer that we want, because this ensures that both

00:17:47.119 --> 00:17:53.119
the before stat data and the before geom data has a Y column present. So then that's what

00:17:53.119 --> 00:17:55.479
finally gets the layer working.

00:17:55.479 --> 00:18:02.280
So that concludes cracking open ggplot internals with ggtrace. Again, ggtrace is helpful. It

00:18:02.280 --> 00:18:07.520
helps us learn the internals as users by exploiting the fact that a lot of the internals is just

00:18:07.520 --> 00:18:12.400
manipulating data frames. And by reframing the internals into familiar data wrangling

00:18:12.400 --> 00:18:17.800
functional programming terms that we're all familiar with, we arrive at a conceptual understanding

00:18:17.800 --> 00:18:23.319
of how the internals work. So this lets us write more powerful ggplot code as users while

00:18:23.319 --> 00:18:28.319
still mostly abstracting away from the scary implementational details like ggproto and

00:18:28.319 --> 00:18:29.800
baseR functions.

00:18:29.800 --> 00:18:33.560
But if you are interested in that, ggtrace has other workflow functions that you can

00:18:33.560 --> 00:18:37.880
use. So just really quickly, there's function from the capture workflow, like ggtrace capture

00:18:37.880 --> 00:18:42.920
fn, which essentially records the behavior of a ggproto method when it executes, and

00:18:42.920 --> 00:18:48.680
then you can have it as a standalone function. You have functions from the hijack workflow,

00:18:48.680 --> 00:18:53.359
which kind of lets you pass or make ggproto methods return arbitrary values, and so you

00:18:53.359 --> 00:18:58.040
can kind of try to hack the internals and see what you can come up with.

00:18:58.040 --> 00:19:01.959
And yeah, that's it. ggtrace is on GitHub. Here's some links to other materials, and

00:19:01.959 --> 00:19:02.880
I'd love to hear your feedback.

